{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538817"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:32:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:32:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16358"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16358"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.73,0.05,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80863"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9049"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66186"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4259"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30665"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80863"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with burns to her chest and abdominal area sustained during a bushfire incident two hours ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker and weighs 60 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears in considerable pain, but her vital signs are within normal limits. She has burns on her chest and abdomen, covering 18% of her total body surface area (TBSA). The burns appear white and waxy with charring. There are no blisters and no capillary refill, consistent with third-degree burns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is going to be started on fluid replacement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following regimens is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1080 mL in the first 8 hours","2160 mL in the first 8 hours","2160 mL in the first 16 hours","4320 mL in the first 8 hours","4320 mL in the first 16 hours"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has significant third-degree burns covering 18% TBSA. The Parkland formula is used to calculate initial fluid requirements: 4 mL \u00d7 weight in kg \u00d7 % TBSA burned. In the case of this patient the calculation is:  4 \u00d7 60 \u00d7 18 = 4320 mL total in 24 hours. Half of this \u003Cstrong\u003E(2160 mL) should be given in the first 8 hours \u003C/strong\u003Eafter the burn, with the remainder over the next 16 hours. This rate may need to be adjusted depending on the individual circumstances. As it has been some two hours since the burn event, the initial rate of infusion in this patient may need to be increased.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1080 mL in the first 8 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would provide insufficient fluid resuscitation according to the Parkland formula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2160 mL in the first 16 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would significantly under-resuscitate the patient during the critical early phase when fluid requirements are highest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4320 mL in the first 8 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would represent over-resuscitation, which can lead to complications such as compartment syndrome, pulmonary oedema, and increased tissue oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4320 mL in the first 16 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would provide too much fluid over that time frame.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile these calculations provide initial guidance, fluid resuscitation should be adjusted based on clinical response, particularly maintaining adequate urine output (0.5-1.0 mL/kg/hour). The modified Parkland formula (3 mL/kg/% TBSA) may be used in some centres to avoid fluid overload, but the principles of early adequate resuscitation remain the same.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Parkland formula (4 mL/kg/% TBSA) is used to calculate initial fluid resuscitation in burns \u003E10% TBSA, with half given in the first 8 hours.","For burns \u003C10% TBSA, maintenance fluids are typically sufficient unless there are other indicators for resuscitation.","The modified Parkland formula (3 mL/kg/% TBSA) is sometimes used to avoid over-resuscitation."],"references":["Diver AJ. The evolution of burn fluid resuscitation. Int J Surg. 2008 Aug;6(4):345-50. doi: 10.1016/j.ijsu.2008.02.003. Epub 2008 Feb 19. PMID: 18448403."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66186"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16358"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66186"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T11:19:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T11:21:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9049"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80863"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemC